AGI - For the first time since the beginning of the conflict in Gaza, the UN Security Council approved a resolution calling for "the immediate ceasefire during Ramadan". The text was approved by the fact that the United States abstained and did not veto as previously. A decision, said the spokesman of the White House National Security Council John Kirby, who "is not a change in our policy". The U.S. abstained on the lack, in the resolution, of a condemnation to Hamas and remain "support of a ceasefire as part of an agreement on the hostages", he explained. But the reaction of Israel did not wait: Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu revoked the Washington mission of a delegation that had to confront the Biden administration on alternatives to a land operation at Rafah. The resolution "damns both the war effort and the attempt to free the hostages, because it gives Hamas the hope that international pressure will allow them to accept a ceasefire without the release of our hostages", explained the Premier's office.
&nbsp;
For the defense minister, Yoav Gallant, on an official visit to the US for meetings with national security adviser Jake Sullivan and state secretary Antony Blinken, Israel "does not have the moral right to stop the war while there are still hostages held in Gaza. The lack of a decisive victory in Gaza could bring us closer to a war in the North." Washington made it clear that Kirby was "very disappointed" by the annulment of the Israeli mission in the United States. Hamas welcomed the UN resolution, reaffirming the request for "a permanent ceasefire that leads to the withdrawal of all Zionist forces from the Gaza Strip and the return of the displaced". The Palestinian group also said "to engage in an immediate process that leads to the release of prisoners of both parties". This resolution must be implemented. The failure would be unforgivable," said the secretary general of the UN Antonio Guterres, who today condemned the stop imposed by Israel to the UNRWA in the delivery of aid in the north of the Strip, calling it "totally unacceptable". </span
